<h2>FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Is the answer economy the same as zero-click search?</strong></p>
<p>Related but different. <a href="/blog/zero-click-search-seo/">Zero-click search</a> describes a specific behavior: users getting answers without clicking. The answer economy describes the broader market shift where AI-generated answers replace traditional search results as the primary discovery channel. Zero-click search is a symptom. The answer economy is the underlying change.</p>
<p><strong>Does the answer economy mean I should stop creating content?</strong></p>
<p>The opposite. AI engines need content to generate answers. The more high-quality, fact-dense content you publish, the more likely you are to be cited. The answer economy rewards content creators who publish consistently with original data and expertise. It punishes those who create thin, generic content.</p>
<p><strong>How do I know if my content gets cited by AI?</strong></p>
<p>Run your target queries through ChatGPT, Perplexity, and Google AI Mode. Check if your brand appears in the response. For automated tracking, use tools like LLMrefs, Semrush AI Visibility, or Otterly. Read our guide on <a href="/blog/llm-visibility-guide/">LLM visibility</a> for the full measurement framework.</p>
<p><strong>What is the difference between AEO and GEO?</strong></p>
<p>Answer Engine Optimization (AEO) focuses on getting cited by AI answer engines like ChatGPT and Perplexity. <a href="/blog/what-is-geo/">Generative Engine Optimization</a> (GEO) is broader, covering all AI-generated search experiences including Google AI Overviews and AI Mode. Both are subsets of the answer economy strategy.</p>
<p><strong>Will Google traffic keep declining?</strong></p>
<p>Total click volume from Google is declining as zero-click queries increase. But the value per click is rising. AI-referred visitors convert at 4.4x higher economic value. The businesses that adapt to the answer economy will generate more revenue from fewer total visitors.</p>
